# Approach
Generator functions (indicated by the ```*``` in ```function*()```) is a function that allows you to iterate throughout code in a function to return different values by calling the same function. While this can be done with regular functions, the conveinent thing with generator functions is they allow you to use the keyword ```yield```, which allows you to stop in the middle of the code and return a value, then when you come back to the function with another call, you pick up where you left off. We can do this using the ```.next().value``` method call, which generator functions automatically have.
1. Initialize the first two numbers in the Fibonacci sequence with ```a = 0``` and ```b = 1```, of which ```a``` will always be smaller than ```b```.
2. Yield value a and value b in succession. When you make the first ```.next().value``` call, it will run into ```yield a``` and return 0, and on the second call will pick off from the ```yield a``` line, run into the ```yield b``` line, and return 1.
3. Make a forever running while loop, so we can generate as many numbers in the sequence as we'd like. In this sequence, we set ```c``` to ```a + b```, and yield the value ```c```. After the ```yield c``` line, set ```a = b``` and ```b = c```, for the next iteration of calculating ```c```.

# Code
```
var fibGenerator = function*() {
    let a = 0;
    let b = 1;
    yield a; // first call returns 0
    yield b; // second call returns 1

    let c;
    while (true) { // third call and after enters this loop
        c = a + b; // calculate c for current call
        yield c; // return c

        // when another call is made, set a and b to next iteration to calculate next c value
        a = b;
        b = c;
    }
};
```
