# Intuition
The intuition behind this approach is to use a generator function to generate Fibonacci numbers on-demand. A generator function allows us to calculate and yield the Fibonacci numbers one by one without storing all of them in memory at once. This approach is memory-efficient and suitable for scenarios where we only need a limited number of Fibonacci numbers.

# Approach
We define the fibGenerator function as a generator function using the function* syntax in JavaScript.
We initialize mylist with the first two Fibonacci numbers [0, 1].
We use the yield keyword to yield the first two Fibonacci numbers (0 and 1) as base cases.
In the for loop, we start calculating the next Fibonacci numbers using the previous two numbers in the mylist array.
We continuously push the new Fibonacci numbers into the mylist array and yield the calculated Fibonacci number using yield num.
The generator will keep generating Fibonacci numbers indefinitely.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
Time complexity: O(1) for each next() call on the generator. Calculating each Fibonacci number takes constant time, so the time complexity of generating one Fibonacci number is constant.

- Space complexity:
Space complexity: O(n) where n is the number of Fibonacci numbers generated. The generator keeps an internal list mylist to store the generated Fibonacci numbers. The space complexity increases as more Fibonacci numbers are generated, but it grows linearly with the number of generated Fibonacci numbers.

# Code
```
/**
 * @return {Generator<number>}
 */
var fibGenerator = function* () {
    let mylist = [0, 1];


    yield mylist[0];
    yield mylist[1];

    for (let i = 2; ; i++) {
        let num = mylist[i - 1] + mylist[i - 2];
        mylist.push(num);
        yield num;
    }
};

/**
 * const gen = fibGenerator();
 * gen.next().value; // 0
 * gen.next().value; // 1
 */
```

