solutions.content:
Ah, good old Fibonacci, the father of Dynamic Programming in the mind of many students. Also, a Tuscan like Leonardo da Vinci, Niccol\xF2 Macchiavelli... and me 😆!

But enough with the trivia bit; assuming we all encountered before, let's go straight to the point, by initially declaring:
* `i`, our pointer, initially set to `0`;
* `fibs`, our collections of Fibonacci numbers.

Our main loop will forever (`while (true)`, since we know the number of calls will never overflow):
* check if `i` is now pointing outside the current boundaries of `fibs` (ie: `i == fibs.length`) and in case append an element given by the sum of the last two to it;
* `yield` `fibs[i]`;
* increase `i` by `1`.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(1)$$ (for each call)
- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$

# Code
```ts
function* fibGenerator(): Generator<number, any, number> {
    let i = 0, fibs = [0, 1];
    while (true) {
        if (i == fibs.length) fibs.push(fibs[i - 1] + fibs[i - 2]);
        yield fibs[i++];
    }
};
```

Can we do better? Well, since we do not need to store the whole sequence, but just the last two values, definitely so!

We will just declare `a` and `b` initially set to be `0` and `1` respectively, `return` `i` for the first `2` iterations and then `return` `b` computed as the sum of the previous two values, updating `a` to take the previous `b` value a we go.

So, for example:

```ts
i = 0, a = 0, b = 1 => i // which is 0 - initial run
i = 1, a = 0, b = 1 => i // which is 1 - second run
i = 2, a = 1, b = 1 => b // which is 1 - third run
i = 2, a = 1, b = 2 => b // which is 2 - fourth run
i = 2, a = 2, b = 3 => b // which is 3 - fifth run
i = 2, a = 3, b = 5 => b // which is 5 - sixth run
i = 2, a = 5, b = 8 => b // which is 5 - seventh run
...
```

Notice we do not even waste computation updating `i` once it reaches the threshold of `2`, just computing the next Fibonacci number in a lazy way.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(1)$$ (for each call)
- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$

# Code
```ts
function* fibGenerator(): Generator<number, any, number> {
    let i = 0, [a, b] = [0, 1];
    while (true) {
        if (i >= 2) [b, a] = [a + b, b]; 
        yield i < 2 ? i++ : b;
    }
};
```

