# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
Classic DFS solution

Main function:
- traverse through all grids
- update ```maxFish``` when some grids returns a larger number from dfs search

In DFS function:
- check conditions: visited? upper lower bounds? water or land? etc
- evaluate grid if condition is fulfilled, then mark as visited = true;
- update the returned value (fish in this case)
- evaluate adjacent grids, check if there's a possible move. Do this recursively to check all possible moves.
- move to adj grids and update returning value (fish)
- If back tracking is necessary, mark as false;

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n^4)$$
- Because we have $$N^2$$ for main function (iterates m*n times), and N (iterates m*n times) for helper dfs function
- So, the time complexity is $$O(m^2*n^2)$$. If m and n are roughly equal (i.e., the grid is close to square), then the time complexity could be described as $$O(N^4)$$ where N is the side length of the grid.  

- Space complexity: $$O(m*n)$$
- The grid itself occupies $$O(m\xD7n)$$ space, but we don't count this since it's given as input. The visited array occupies $$O(m\xD7n)$$ space. The recursive DFS can potentially go as deep as m\xD7n in the worst case, so the call stack could occupy $$O(m\xD7n)$$ space. 
- Combining the above, the total space complexity is $$O(m\xD7n)$$.

# Code
```
class Solution {

    int [][] directions = {{0,1},{1,0},{0,-1},{-1,0}};

    public int findMaxFish(int[][] grid) { 
        // DFS to find spot with maxfish && maxFish > 0
        int m = grid.length, n = grid[0].length; // m >= 1; n <= 10;
        int maxFish = 0;
        int fish = 0;
        // use two for-loops to traverse through all grids
        for(int i = 0; i < m; i++ ){
            for(int j = 0; j < n; j++){
                fish = dfs(i,j,grid,new boolean [m][n]); // don't use visited[i][j] here because 
                maxFish = Math.max(fish,maxFish); //update if newly collected fish is more
            }
        }
        return maxFish;
    }
    private int dfs(int r, int c, int[][] grid, boolean[][] visited){
        int m = grid.length, n = grid[0].length;
        //check all conditions: visited ? water? reach bound m? n?
        if (r < 0 || r >= m || c < 0 || c >= n || visited[r][c] || grid[r][c] <= 0) {
            return 0;
        }
        // update visited
        visited[r][c] = true;

        //if passed, update new fish num
        int fish = grid[r][c];
        grid[r][c] = 0; // set land mark to 0 to avoid double counting

        // keep updating fish if adj routes are possible
        for(int[] dir : directions){
            int adjrow = r + dir[0];
            int adjcol = c + dir[1];
            fish += dfs(adjrow,adjcol,grid,visited);
        }

        //update if backtrack
        visited[r][c] = false;

        return fish;
    }
}
```

