# Approach
**DFS** through every non-zero cell, and add up all the numbers found on the way. Also, mark all the cells as 0, so they won't be parsed again.
Every DFS dive will get back a number, that will be the maximum number of fishes caught starting from current cell, as well as from any cell that was visited.No need to do it again from every cell.
Biggest number returned among all dfs dives will be the answer.

# Complexity
Let rows and columns be denoted by ```row```, ```col```
- Time complexity:
At worst case parsing of every cell in the grid:$$O(row*col)$$
**Total: $$O(row * col)$$**

- Space complexity:
Excluding input: **$$O(1)$$**
Including input: **$$O(row * col)$$**


# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int findMaxFish(int[][] grid) {
        int max = 0;
        int row = grid.length,col = grid[0].length;
        for(int i=0;i<row;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<col;j++){
                if(grid[i][j] == 0) continue;
                int count = dfs(grid,i,j,row,col);
                max = Math.max(max,count);
            }
        }
        return max;
    }

    int dfs(int[][] arr,int i,int j,int row,int col){
        if(i<0 || j<0 || i>=row || j>=col) return 0;
        if(arr[i][j] == 0) return 0;
        int count = arr[i][j];
        arr[i][j] = 0;

        count+=dfs(arr,i+1,j,row,col);
        count+=dfs(arr,i,j+1,row,col);
        count+=dfs(arr,i-1,j,row,col);
        count+=dfs(arr,i,j-1,row,col);

        return count;
    }
}
```

