We tack the maximum the path sum, and for each non-leaf node, we "pick up the slack".

The top-down solution is easier to comprehend; once you get it - it should be easy to code the bottom-up approach.

## Top-Down

**C++**
```cpp
array<int, 2> path_sum(int i, int n, vector<int>& cost) {
    if (i * 2 >= n)
        return {0, cost[i - 1]};
    auto l = path_sum(i * 2, n, cost), r = path_sum(i * 2 + 1, n, cost);
    return {l[0] + r[0] + abs(l[1] - r[1]), cost[i - 1] + max(l[1], r[1])};
}     
int minIncrements(int n, vector<int>& cost) {
    return path_sum(1, n, cost)[0];
}
```

