Description:
The task is to find the minimum number of increment operations required to make all the paths in a given binary tree with given cost values equal. This can be achieved by first calculating the maximum path sum in the binary tree and then finding the minimum number of operations required to make each path equal to the maximum path sum.
Intution:
We can always make all paths equal by incrementing those leaf nodes where path sum is less than the maximum.
In order to calculate the minimum operations we wil first do all the operations at last. Now at an arbitrary level which is non-root and non-leaf level we will do the minimum of operations done by it left and right child and decrease our total operations by same as we our doing operations on a common node. we will return number of operations done at this level to upperlevels.
```
class Solution {
    int myN,max;
    int ans=0;
    public int minIncrements(int n, int[] cost) {
        myN = n;
        max =  helper(0,cost);
        helper2(0,0,cost);
        return ans;
    }
	//to calculate maximum path sum.
    int helper(int i,int[] cost){
        if(i>=myN) return 0;
        int left = helper(2*i+1,cost);
        int right = helper(2*i+2,cost);
        return cost[i]+Math.max(left,right);
    }
	//to calculate minimum operations
    int helper2(int i,int sum,int[] cost){
        if(i>=myN){
			//update answer with operations needed
            ans+=(max-sum);
            return max-sum;
        }
		//get operations done by lower leverls.
        int left = helper2(2*i+1,sum+cost[i],cost);
        int right = helper2(2*i+2,sum+cost[i],cost);

		//reduce ans by min left,right
        ans-=(Math.min(left,right));
        return Math.min(left,right);
    }
}
```

