# Intuition
We want our binary tree to verify the equal path property (the cost to go from root to any leaf has to be the same). I will call a binary tree which verifies this property balanced.
The key logic is the following:

The optimal strategy is to ensure every subtree is balanced

Why is this true? Well, let’s imagine that there is a subtree rooted at a node subroot which is unbalanced. That is to say it can reach a certain leaf1 for lowcost, and another leaf2 for a different highcost.
Well, in that case, its parent node will reach leaf1 for lowcost+cost[subroot] and leaf2 for highcost+cost[subroot], which are different costs. We see that the unbalanced property is recursive: if any subtree is unbalanced, it will “contaminate” the parent.
![56b9ad51-e064-459f-a063-513c10ce5d02_1683437244.2906523.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/0a60aa6d-095d-4480-a3e0-804d77d7f2f8_1683439721.0159767.png)


Therefore, if we want to balance root, it is necessary to balance every subroot on its way. It is easy to verify that this is also a sufficient condition. So this is the optimal way to do it, because it is in fact the only way to do it! (root is balanced if and only if all of the subtrees are balanced)

That begs for a recursive approach! If we ensure starting from every leaf, that every subtree is balanced, then it’s easy to make the right corrections to balance the parent too!


Approach
Let’s do a recursive dfs.

We position ourselves at a specific node subroot and will treat it as the root of a subtree. We assume that all of its subtrees are already balanced (done earlier in the recursion). Then its left child reaches all leaves for leftcost, and the right child for rightcost. We just need to make a correction according to the difference between those two (correction+=abs(leftcost-rightcost)) to balance the subroot.

We then return the total cost of this subroot which is simply max(leftcost,rightcost)+cost[subroot]. The maximum is taken here because we can only increment, so that means after we balance a subtree, its cost to leaf will be set to the largest of the initial values.

And that’s it! If this helped you understand the proof of correctness and visualize it, do leave an upvote, it is always encouraging!
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int ans=0;
    int dfs (int node ,vector<int>&cost)
    {    
        if(node>cost.size())return 0;
        int left=0 ,right=0;
        left= dfs(2*node,cost);
        right=dfs(2*node+1,cost);
        ans+=abs(left-right);
        return cost[node-1]+max(left,right);
    }
    int minIncrements(int N, vector<int>& cost)
    {
        dfs(1,cost);
        return ans;
    }
};
```

