# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- Build the solution from the leaves upwards
- Relies on this invariant of `dfs`: add the correct number of increments for the current subtree to `res` and return its total cost
- Thus, when the algorithm comes back to the root, the left and right subtrees have already been solved and what's left is to compare their heights and add the number of increments to make up their difference

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

$$ O(n) $$

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

$$ O(h) $$, where $$ h $$ is height

# Code
```
class Solution {
private:
    int res;

public:
    int minIncrements(int n, vector<int>& cost) {
        dfs(1, cost, n);
        return res;
    }

    int dfs(int root, vector<int>& cost, int n) {
        if (root > n) {
            return 0;
        }

        int leftLen = dfs(root * 2, cost, n);
        int rightLen = dfs(root * 2 + 1, cost, n);
        res += abs(leftLen - rightLen);
        return cost[root - 1] + max(leftLen, rightLen);
    }
};
```

