# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Since we could only increment, we should not modify the largest path.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
With the post-order traversal approach, it becomes easy to find the sum path of the left and right subtrees. Based on this idea, we can try to equalize the cost of the left and right subtrees. To achieve this, we can calculate the absolute difference between the costs of the left and right subtrees using the expression ***abs(left - right)***. This value represents the minimum number of operations required to balance the two subtrees. Then return ***current cost + max(left, right)*** since we have balance the two sub-tree.
# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Traversed all the nodes once
- Space complexity: O(n)
