solutions.content:
First of all, there must be a maximum cost path exist in the tree, then each other path should get the final addition equal to the max cost path. We get that max and record max path of every tree root node.

How do we get max cost of every root node? We iterate from the back n to 1, if the root node is a leaf, that max cost is the cost[i] itself, if the root node has children, max cost of the root node is Math.max(leftchild, rightchild) + cost[i].

Secondly, If we want to get the minimum addition, we should add the most from the root node.
```
public int minIncrements(int n, int[] cost) {
	int[] dp = new int[n+1];
	//first we record max cost path of each tree root node
	for(int i=n; i>=1; i--){
		if(2*i+1 <= n){
			dp[i] = Math.max(dp[i*2], dp[i*2+1]) + cost[i-1];
		}else{
			dp[i] = cost[i-1];
		}
	}
	int[] res = new int[1];
	int max = dp[1];
	dsf(1, max, n, cost, dp, res);

	return res[0];
}
void dsf(int root, int max, int n, int[] cost, int[] dp, int[] res){
	if(root > n) return;

	int diff = max - dp[root];
	int newmax = 0;
	if(diff == 0){
		newmax = max - cost[root-1];
	}else{
		newmax = max - (diff + cost[root-1]);
		res[0] += diff;
	}

	int left = root * 2;
	dsf(left, newmax, n, cost, dp, res);
	int right = root * 2 + 1;
	dsf(right, newmax, n, cost, dp, res);
}
```

