solutions.content:
Let original array be:
[A, B, C, D, E, F]
then derived array will be:
[A⊕B, B⊕C, C⊕D, D⊕E, E⊕F, F⊕A]
now, if you take xor of all the elements in derived array, it will be:
A⊕B ⊕ B⊕C ⊕ C⊕D ⊕ D⊕E ⊕ E⊕F ⊕ F⊕A = 0
as all the elements are appears twice (and  A⊕A = 0)
......................................................................................
or if not convinced with twice argument, you can follow the operations 
A⊕B ⊕ B⊕C ⊕ C⊕D ⊕ D⊕E ⊕ E⊕F ⊕ F⊕A as:
**A⊕B ⊕ B⊕C** ⊕ C⊕D ⊕ D⊕E ⊕ E⊕F ⊕ F⊕A = **A⊕C** ⊕ C⊕D ⊕ D⊕E ⊕ E⊕F ⊕ F⊕A
&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;&nbsp;**A⊕C ⊕ C⊕D** ⊕ D⊕E ⊕ E⊕F ⊕ F⊕A = **A⊕D** ⊕ D⊕E ⊕ E⊕F ⊕ F⊕A 
-> follow this chain to arrive to **A⊕A** = 0
......................................................................................
this result is **general** and doesn't limit our derived array to be 0 1 only and would work on any **input array**.
If derived array is only 0 1 as in our case, as an **alternate solution**, we can just count number of 1's, which should be even
as it is the special case of our xor result. Even number of 1's will cancel out each other while taking xor.
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool doesValidArrayExist(vector<int>& derived) {
        int x = 0;
        for(int y: derived) x ^= y;
        return x == 0;
    }
};
```

