# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

Since the 'derived' binary array is the result of an XOR operation we have information about the original vector. Every bit in the derived vector contains comparison information about the original vector:
> every 1 must be the result of (0 xor 1) or (1 xor 0), i.e. neighbors were different 
> every 0 must be the result of (0 xor 0) or (1 xor 1), i.e. neighbors were the same

Example:
derived = [1, 1, 0]
> original [0] != original [1]
> original [1] != original [2]
> original [2] == original [0]

derived = [1, 1]
> original [0] != original [1]
> original [1] != original [0]

derived = [1, 0]
> original [0] != original [1]
> original [1] == original [0]
>> a contradiction!!

derived = [1, 0, 1]
> original [0] != original [1]
> original [1] == original [2]
> original [2] != original [0]

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
This approach isn't the fastest, but constructs a pluasible original vector.

We start by initializing our original vector with 0, (it doesn't matter if the original vector is initialized with a 0 or 1, since we only know the comparison information anyways.)

Then, we iterate through the derived vector, and keep adding bits to the original vector:

The next bit to add to the original vector will be:
> The same as the last bit added if the derived vector is (0)
> The opposite as the last bit added if the derived vector is (1)

Finally, to see if the original vector is valid we look at the last bit of comparison information in the derived vector, which compares the first and last bits. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n)

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool doesValidArrayExist(vector<int>& derived) {
        vector<int> original;
        original.push_back(0); // assume a starting bit

        // add bits to original vector, based on the comparison information in the derived bit vector.
        // if a bit in the derived vector is::
        //                 '1' -> meaning the neighbor bits in the original were different
        //                 '0' -> meaning the neighbor bits in the original were the same
        for(int i = 0; i < derived.size()-1; i ++){
            if (derived.at(i) == 0){
                original.push_back(original.at(i));
            } else {
                original.push_back(!original.at(i));
            }
        }
        // to determine if a valid array exists, we determine if the comparison information in the derived bit vector 
        // is consistant with the start and end bits of our constructed 'original' vector.
        if (derived.back() == 0){
            return original.front() == original.back();
        } else {
            return original.front() != original.back();
        }
    }
};

```

