# Important things to understand
```
X ^ X = 0
2 ^ 2 = 0

X ^ X ^ Y ^ Y = 0
2 ^ 5 ^ 2 ^ 5 = 0

```
It means that if same element is XORed even times then it becomes 0

```
X ^ Y ^ X = Y  
1 ^ 5 ^ 1 = 5 

```
Here the output becomes the element which appeard odd times and the elements appeared even times were cancelled out.

# Derived Array
Suppose we have an `Original array` `[A B C D]`. The `Derived array`, by definition, will be `[A xor B, B xor C, C xor D, D xor A]`. Here we can see that every element of the `Original array` appears twice in the `Derived array`.

# Approach
So whenever we derive an array from `original array` consisting `1's` and `0's`. The `Derived array` will always contain `even` no. of `1's`because we now know that every element appears twice to construct the`Derived array`

So it is not possible to contain`odd` number of `1's` in the `Derived array` , if that is the case we will `return false` or else `return true`.

# Solution
`Now we have 2 solutions: `
1. we can perform `XOR` operation on all elements of the `Derived array`

    example 1: `[1,1,0]`    1 ^ 1 ^ 0 = 0, Ans is `True` because 1 appeared even times     

    example 2: `[1,1,0,1]` 1 ^ 1 ^ 0 ^ 1 = 1, Ans is `False` because 1 appeared odd times

```
class Solution {
    public boolean doesValidArrayExist(int[] derived) {
        int ans = 0;
        for(int i=0; i<derived.length; i++){
            ans ^= derived[i];
        }
        return ans==0; 
    }
} 
```
2. We can simply count the number of `1's `in the `derived array` and if the count of `1` is `even` we'll return `true` or else `false`;

```
class Solution {
    public boolean doesValidArrayExist(int[] derived) {
        int ans = 0;
        for(int i=0; i<derived.length; i++){
            ans += derived[i];
        }
        return ans%2==0; 
    }
} 
```

