**Solution-1**
2 ways to make original array

original1[0] = 0 (array starting with 0)
original2[0] = 1 (array starting wiht 1)

and then keep building more on both of the arrays.

If any of the array (either original1 or original2) satifies then return true else false.
```
class Solution {
public:

    bool doesValidArrayExist(vector<int>& derived) {
        int n=derived.size();
        vector<int>original1(n);
        vector<int>original2(n);
        original1[0]=0;
        original2[0]=1;

        for(int i=1;i<n;i++)
        {
            original1[i]=derived[i-1] ^ original1[i-1];
            original2[i]=derived[i-1] ^ original2[i-1];
        }
        return ((derived[n-1]==original1[n-1]^original1[0]) || (derived[n-1]==original2[n-1]^original2[0]));

    }
};
```

**Solution-2**
derived[0] = original[0] ^ original[1]
derived[1] = original[1] ^ original[2]
derived[2] = original[2] ^ original[3]
...
derived[n-2] = original[n-2] ^ original[n-1]
derived[n-1] = original[n-1] ^ original[0]

On xoring both the sides

LHS
derived[0] ^ derived[1] ^ derived[2] ^ ... ^ derived[n-1] => same as xoring entire derived array.

RHS
since every element will appear twice so it will result into zero.

Hence valid binary array original will exist only when xor(derived) = zero.

Summary:
Every element is appearing twice in the entire process.
That means at the end if xor of the entire element =0 then there exists a valid binary array, otherwise not.

