solutions.content:
**for…in**
This statement will loop through the enumerable property of the object.
```
function isEmpty(obj: Record<string, any> | any[]): boolean {
    for (const prop in obj) {
        if (obj.hasOwnProperty(prop)) {
            return false;
        }   
    }
    return true;
};
```

**Object.keys**
It will return an array, which contains the property names of the object. If the length of the array is 0, then we know that the object is empty. **(In my opinion, this is the easiest)**
```
function isEmpty(obj: Record<string, any> | any[]): boolean {
    return Object.keys(obj).length === 0;
};
```

**JSON.stringify**
The object and the result is simply an opening and closing bracket, we know the object is empty.
```
function isEmpty(obj: Record<string, any> | any[]): boolean {
   return JSON.stringify(obj) === '{}' || JSON.stringify(obj) === '[]';
};
```

