# Approach 1 (Gives TLE)
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

Let's say the minimum operations are k.
The power of 2 that is subtracted from num1 in the operations are n1, n2, n3 ..... nk.

Thus, the problem becomes as follows :
![TLE-Explain.jpg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/75426a0d-ee2c-4206-88db-126861a8cc9d_1687986847.891799.jpeg)

The question actually boils down to :
Can a number be represented as a sum of exactly k numbers which all are a power of 2?

![Recursion-Explain.jpg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/ca96d345-98b8-41ec-b39e-cff38af7a989_1687987854.6343074.jpeg)


# Complexity
- Time complexity: O((num1/num2)*num1)
>> (num1/num2) for the main function while(num1-k*num2>0) since here k can take max num1/num2 values. 
Then for every loop, we were checking check_count function which is recursively calling with (num1) complexity.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(1) + Stack Space
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool check_count(long long int num, int count){
        if(num==0 && count==0){
            return true;
        }
        if(num==0 || count==0){
            return false;
        }

        long long int power = 1;
        while(power<=num){
            if(check_count(num-power,count-1)){
                return true;
            }
            power=power*2;
        }
        return false;
    }

    int makeTheIntegerZero(int num1, int num2) {
        if(num1<num2){
            return -1;
        }

        int k = 0;
        while(num1-k*num2>0){
            long long int val = num1-k*num2;

            if(check_count(val,k)){
                return k;
            }
            k++;
        }

        return -1;
    }
};
```

# Approach 2 (Accepted + Beats 100%)
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Here also the problem boils down to the same thing : Can we represent a number as sum of exactly k numbers which are a power of 2?

Now here are the points to note:
1. The minimum value of number of powers of two required to make a digit is equal to the number of set bits in that number.
2. The maximum value of number powers of two required to make a digit is equal to that number itself.

![MaxMin.jpg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/341a32a1-fa58-4b2e-9f42-a636840f6920_1687989179.7718656.jpeg)

3. A number can be represented as a sum of k powers of 2, where k lies between the above minimum and maximum (both inclusive). Here's an example how : 

![Explain2.jpg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/815fa52f-86ab-4d8b-81e3-c0460fad690d_1687989817.1418333.jpeg)


Thus, for a number, it can be represented as a sum of k powers of 2, if k lies between number of set bits in that number and that number itself (both inclusive).

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(num1)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int count_bits(long long int num){
        int count = 0;
        while(num){
            if(num&1){
                count++;
            }
            num=num>>1;
        }
        return count;
    }

    int makeTheIntegerZero(int num1, int num2) {
        num1*=1LL;
        num2*=1LL;
        if(num1<num2){
            return -1;
        }

        long long int k = 0;
        while(num1-k*num2>0){
            long long int diff = num1-k*num2;
            int bits_count = count_bits(diff);

            if(k<=diff && k>=bits_count){
                return k;
            }
            k++;
        }

        return -1;
    }
};
```

