# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The intuition is of using Bits Manipulation.
Suppose k is the minimum number of operations to make num1 equals to zero.
Now we can write something like nums1 - ((2^i1 + nums2) + (2^i2 + nums2) + (2^i3 + nums2) + ... and so on upto k times).
I can also write it like nums1 - (2^i1 + 2^i2 + 2^i3 + .. upto ktimes) - (k*nums2).

Now, from here we can conclude that the max value of k can be upto 60(although it won't be more than 32) only becuase (2^i1 + 2^i2 + 2^i3 + ...) is nothing just the binary representation of any number and at max we can have all bits set.

Now let the number (2^i1 + 2^i2 + 2^i3 + ...) be X. So, we can write nums1 - (X + k*nums2).
Now our target is to make it zero.
- nums1 - X - k*nums2 = 0
- X = nums1 - k*nums2

Now just run a loop of i from 0 to 60 and just find nums1 - i * nums2. Now this number is X. Now we will count the number of set bits in it. 
- If the number of set bits is more than i, then this can't be our answer
- If the number of set bits is less than or equal to i then this can be our answer. Because above we have assumed i1, i2, i3, .. to be different but it may happen that i1 , i2, i3,.. can be same. And if that happen then the number of set bits will decrease.
- We have to take care of some edge cases also. The first edge case is the count of bits should not be zero because this is not possible. The second edge case is X should be greater than or equal to k because at min we can subtract 1 from nums1.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(1)$$

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(1)$$

# Code
