# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Forget about the num2 and just think about the minimum and maximum operations required to reduce a number to zero.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The minimum operations required to reduce a number to 0 will be the count of set bits in the number. And the max operations will be equal to the number itself.
Just check if this condition hold for every operation count between 0 and 61.
If not decrease num1 by num2.
# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(1)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->


- Space complexity: O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int makeTheIntegerZero(int num1, int num2) {
        if (num2 > num1)return -1;
        int operation = 0;
        long long number1 = (long long)num1;
        long long number2 = (long long)num2;

        while(number1 >=0 && operation < 61){
            int count = __builtin_popcountll(number1);
            if(operation >= count && operation <= number1){
                return operation;
            }

            operation++;
            number1 -= number2;
        }

        return -1;
    }
};
```

