# Intuition
According to constraints, if we directly apply memoization we will definetely get memory limit exceeded, as we need to maintain a prev pointer
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
In this approach we are clubbing consecutive even and odd numbers to form a new vector ```temp ``` 

Suppose in given example:
```nums = [2,3,6,1,9,2]```
The new temp would be
```temp = [2,3,6,10,2]```

Note that in this example, in even indices, the sums are coming from even numbers and in odd indices sum is coming from odd numbers, see the pattern by taking other examples

Now in this new ```temp``` we are applying pick and not-pick type algorithm

If we want to pick the element then if parity of both is same then we directly pick the number, otherwise we will subtract ```x```.
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Memoization
- Time complexity: ```O(n)```
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: ```O(n * 2) + O(n)``` 
    ```O(n*2)``` for ```dp``` vector and``` O(n)``` for forming ```temp``` vector in worst case
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
```
class Solution {
    vector<vector<long long>> dp;
    int n;
    long long f(int i, vector<long long> &nums, int x, bool prev) {
        if(i >= n) return 0;
        if(dp[i][prev] != -1) return dp[i][prev];

        int scoreDiff = ((i&1) == prev) ? 0 : -x;

        // if nums[i] is even then i&1 will be zero otherwise one
        long long pick = nums[i] + f(i+1, nums, x, i&1) + scoreDiff;

        long long notPick = f(i+1, nums, x, prev);

        return dp[i][prev] = max(pick, notPick);
    }
public:
    long long maxScore(vector<int>& nums, int x) {
        n = nums.size();
        vector<long long> temp;
        temp.reserve(n);
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            long long mist = nums[i];
            while (i < n - 1 && ((nums[i] & 1) == (nums[i + 1] & 1))) {
                mist += nums[i + 1];
                i++;
            }
            temp.push_back(mist);
        }
        n = temp.size();
        dp.resize(n+1, vector<long long>(2, -1));
        return temp[0] + f(1, temp, x, 0);
    }
};

```

# Tabulation 
- Time complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: Same as memoization
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
```
class Solution {
    vector<vector<long long>> dp;
    int n;
public:
    long long maxScore(vector<int>& nums, int x) {
        n = nums.size();
        vector<long long> temp;
        temp.reserve(n);
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            long long mist = nums[i];
            while (i < n - 1 && ((nums[i] & 1) == (nums[i + 1] & 1))) {
                mist += nums[i + 1];
                i++;
            }
            temp.push_back(mist);
        }

        n = temp.size();
        dp.resize(n+1, vector<long long>(2, 0));

        for(int i=n-1; i>=1; i--) {
            for(int prev = 1; prev >= 0; prev--) {
                int scoreDiff = ((i&1) == prev) ? 0 : -x;

                // if nums[i] is even then i&1 will be zero otherwise one
                long long pick = temp[i] + dp[i+1][i&1] + scoreDiff;        
                long long notPick = dp[i+1][prev];

                dp[i][prev] = max(pick, notPick);
            }
        }

        return temp[0] + dp[1][0];
    }
};
```

# Space Optimization
- Time complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: ```O(n)``` just for ```temp``` vector in worst case
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
