solutions.content:
### dynamic programming - choose or not
dfs(i, is_odd) is max score we can get in nums[i:] and is_odd is if number we take last time is odd or not.

if current number nums[i]'s parity is the same as the number we take last time,
we should choose it.

if not, we have 2 options, choose or skip it.
if we choose it, we get nums[i] - x score, and parity of last number will be changed.
if we skip it, we get nothing, keep parity.


dfs(i, is_odd) = nums[i] + dfs(i+1, is_odd) if nums[i] % 2 == is_odd
or
dfs(i, is_odd) = max(nums[i] - x + dfs(i+1, nums[i] % 2), dfs(i+1, is_odd)).

tc is O(n), sc is O(n).

### python
```python
class Solution:
    def maxScore(self, nums: List[int], x: int) -> int:
        size = len(nums)
        @cache
        def dfs(i, is_odd):
            if i == size: return 0
            y = nums[i]
            if y % 2 == is_odd:
                return y + dfs(i+1, is_odd)
            return max(dfs(i+1, is_odd), y - x + dfs(i+1, y % 2))
        return dfs(0, nums[0] % 2)
```

### c++
```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    long long maxScore(vector<int>& nums, int x) {
        int size = nums.size();
        vector<vector<long long>> dp (size, vector<long long> (2, LLONG_MIN));
        function<long long(int, int)> dfs = [&] (int i, int is_odd) {
            if (i == size) return 0LL;
            if (dp[i][is_odd] != LLONG_MIN) return dp[i][is_odd];
            if (nums[i] % 2 == is_odd) return nums[i] + dfs(i+1, is_odd);
            long long sub = max(nums[i] - x + dfs(i+1, is_odd ^ 1), dfs(i+1, is_odd));
            return dp[i][is_odd] = sub;
        };
        return dfs(0, nums[0] % 2);
    }
};
```
