solutions.content:
# Intuition

We need to follow the parity (even/odd) of the values in the array `nums`. If we are at an index $i$, then the next step will be at an index $j>i$. There are two possibilities
- If `nums[i]` and `nums[i+1]` have the same parity, then we may move from `i` to `i+1` to gain `nums[i+1]` points. This still allow us to move to any other position $j>i$ to gain points from then on.
- However, it `nums[i]` and `nums[i+1]` have different parities, we could move from `i` to the next index `j` such that `nums[i]` and `nums[j]` have the same parity (to avoid losing $x$ points), or it could be worth it to mode from `i` to `i+1`, if from `i+1` we can gain enough points to compensate the `x` points lost.

Thus, we get a backwards recursion on the maximum amount of points we can get: Let `maxPoints[i]` be the maximum amount of points we can obtain starting at index `i`. Then
- `maxPoints[numsSize-1] = nums[numsSize-1]`
- If `nums[i]` and `nums[i+1]` have the same parity, then `maxPoints[i] = nums[i] + maxPoints[i+1]`.
- If `nums[i]` and `nums[i+1]` have distinct parities, then `maxPoints[i] = nums[i] + max(maxPoints[i+1]-x , maxPoints[j])`, where `j>i` is the smallest index such that `nums[i]` and `nums[j]` have the same parity.

    (If no `j` exist, substitute `maxPoints[j]` in this formula by `0`, which is the same as ending the point-obtaining steps.)


# Recursive Approach (TLE)

The following is the simple, unoptimized recursive approach, obtained by simply translating the algorithm above. This gives us TLE, even for small (48 element-) arrays. This is because each computation of the recursive function makes 2 recursive calls.

```
long long maxScore_(const int* nums, const int numsSize, const int x, int i){
    if (i==numsSize-1) return nums[i];
    if (nums[i]%2 == nums[i+1]%2) {
        // Same parity
        return nums[i] + maxScore_(nums, numsSize, x, i+1);
    }

    // Find the next index with same parity as nums[i]
    int j = i+1;
    while (j<numsSize && (nums[i]%2 != nums[j] %2)) ++j;

    if (j==numsSize) {
        // No index with same parity
        return nums[i] + MAX(maxScore_(nums, numsSize, x, i+1)-x , 0);
    }
    return nums[i] + MAX(maxScore_(nums, numsSize, x, i+1)-x , maxScore_(nums, numsSize, x, j));
}


long long maxScore(int* nums, int numsSize, int x){
    return maxScore_(nums , numsSize, x , 0);
}
```

## Complexity

- Time and space complexity: $O\left(\left(\dfrac{1+\sqrt{5}}{2}\right)^n\right)$ (Fibonacci)

The obvious way to solve this problem is by DP.

# Unoptimized DP approach

We store the values of the maximum points obtainable from starting from index `i` in a value `dp[i]`, which gives us a DP table/array `dp[]`, with the same length as the original array. This table is filled according to the recursive rule.

Since `dp[i]` always depends directly on `dp[i+1]`, we implement a bottom-up approach (starting from the end and going to the beginning of the DP table).

```
#define MAX(a,b) (a>=b ? a : b)

long long maxScore(int* nums, int numsSize, int x){
    long long * dp = malloc(numsSize*sizeof(long long));
    // Holds the maximum score obtainable from each index
    dp[numsSize-1] = nums[numsSize-1];
    int i=numsSize-2;
    while (i>=0) {
        if (nums[i]%2 == nums[i+1]%2) {
            // Same parity
            dp[i] = nums[i] + dp[i+1];
        } else {
            int j=i+1;
            // Find the next index with same parity as nums[i]
            while (j<numsSize && !(nums[i]%2 == nums[j]%2)) ++j;
            if (j==numsSize) {
                // No index with same parity
                if (dp[i+1]>x) {
                    dp[i] = nums[i] + dp[i+1]-x;
                } else {
                    dp[i] = nums[i];
                }
            } else {
                // nums[j] ans nums[i] have the same parity
                dp[i] = nums[i] + MAX(dp[i+1]-x , dp[j]);
            }
        }
        --i;
    }

    return dp[0];
}
``` 

## Complexity

- Time and space complexity: $O(n)$.

This works well and solves the problem, however it is in the lower 20% of space and time efficiency



# Optimized DP approach

When computing the DP table in the approach above, the problem of computing `dp[i]` in terms of `dp[j]` ($j>i$) depends on whether `nums[i]` and `nums[j]` have the same parity. But in fact we do not care about the values of `num[j]` for ***all*** $j>i$, but only the two smallest values of $j$ for which `num[j]` has the same or a different parity than `nums[i]`.

Thus, it is sufficient to only store values in our DP table which tell us the maximum obtainable points from a given index, starting from an index `j` for which `nums[j]` is odd or even. In this sense, `dp[i]` is computed as follows:

> Choose the next index `j>i` such that the maximum obtainable points from `j` are the largest, even if `nums[j]` has a different parity from `nums[i]`.

By storing those maximum values for both `nums[j]` even and odd, we obtain our recursive rule: Let `dp[even]` and `dp[odd]` be the maximum attainable points which may be obtained by starting the game from an index `j>i` for which `nums[j]` is even and odd, respectively. Then

`dp[i] = nums[i] + MAX(dp[parity(i))] , dp[not(parity(i))]-x)`

Then the value of `dp[parity of i]` is updated with this `dp[i]`.

A few minor optimizations apart (using `&1` to compute parity instead of `%2`; `register` and `const` keywords), we implement this code as our final solution.

```
#define MAX(a,b) (a>=b ? a : b)

long long maxScore(const int* nums, const int numsSize, const int x){
    long dp[2] = {0};
    // dp[0] is dp of even value for nums[i]
    // dp[1] is dp of odd value for nums[i];
    // That is; dp[nums[i]%2] is the dp of the right parity

    // Holds the maximum score obtainable from each index
    register int parity = nums[numsSize-1] & 1;
    dp[parity] = nums[numsSize-1];
    for ( int i=numsSize-2 ; i>=0 ; --i) {
        parity = nums[i] & 1;
        dp[parity] = nums[i] + MAX(dp[!parity]-x , dp[parity]);
    }
    // Parity holds the parity of nums[0]
    return dp[parity];
}
```

