solutions.content:
Nice problem to practice some Dynamic Programming (henceforth: "DP"), since we have
* a base case (when we have only one element to add and we come from either an even or an odd previous sum);
* a general one (when we have multiple elements left).

We can solve it by parsing our input and having a store of the past states; we might be tempted to store all the previous states as we go, but in reality we only need two - one for the best even and one for the best odd sum we can get.

To do so, let's start declaring our support variables:
* `len` will store the length of our input;
* `dp` is an array of two elements, our even and odd case.

We will then write `nums[0]` in both cells of `dp`, then subtract `x` by the one not having parity with `nums[0]` (ie: `nums[!(nums[0] & 1)]`).

Now we can proceed, sorting all the elements from the second with `i` going from `1` to the end of the series and:
* storing `nums[i]` in `n`;
* storing our parity (ie: `n & 1`) in `curr`;
* if we are currently dealing with an odd `n` (ie: `curr == 1`), we will set `dp[1]` to be the maximum between its current value and `dp[0] - x`, both additioned with `n`;
* specularly for an even case, we will set `dp[0]` to be the maximum between its current value and `dp[1] - x`, both additioned with `n`.

Once done, we will `return` the maximum between the even and odd scenarios (ie: `max(dp[0], dp[1])`).

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$

# Code
```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    long long maxScore(vector<int>& nums, int x) {
        // support variables
        int len = nums.size();
        long long dp[2];
        // preparing dp
        dp[0] = dp[1] = nums[0];
        dp[!(nums[0] & 1)] -= x;
        // updating dp with each value after the first
        for (int i = 1, n, curr; i < len; i++) {
            n = nums[i], curr = n & 1;
            // odd case:
            if (curr) dp[1] = max(dp[1], dp[0] - x) + n;
            // even case:
            else dp[0] = max(dp[0], dp[1] - x) + n;
        }
        return max(dp[0], dp[1]);
    }
};
```
Or we can make it even more concise, by already setting `dp` with the right starting values and avoiding the conditional inside our loop and just using `curr` to decide what is needed:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    long long maxScore(vector<int>& nums, int x) {
        // support variables
        int len = nums.size();
        long long dp[2] = {nums[0], nums[0]};
        // preparing dp
        dp[!(nums[0] & 1)] -= x;
        // updating dp with each value after the first
        for (int i = 1, n, curr; i < len; i++) {
            n = nums[i], curr = n & 1;
            dp[curr] = max(dp[curr], dp[!curr] - x) + n;
        }
        return max(dp[0], dp[1]);
    }
};
```

Or we can just have the loop take all the elements, as long as we just initialise `dp` to be `0` and `-x` for the elements matching and not matching the parity of `nums[0]`, respectively:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    long long maxScore(vector<int>& nums, int x) {
        // support variables
        int len = nums.size();
        long long dp[2] = {};
        bool curr = !(nums[0] & 1);
        // preparing dp
        dp[curr] -= x;
        // updating dp with each value after the first
        for (int n: nums) {
            curr = n & 1;
            dp[curr] = max(dp[curr], dp[!curr] - x) + n;
        }
        return max(dp[0], dp[1]);
    }
};
```

