# Intuition
Important part is to notice that this is a DP problem and you need to know only two values (`max_odd`, `max_even`) and at any step the recurrence relationship is:

```
if el % 2 == 1 {
  max_even = max(max_even + el, max_odd + el - x)
} else {
  max_odd  = max(max_odd + el, max_even + el - x)
}
```

Now all we need is to find starting values. They depend on the parity of `nums[0]`: `max_odd, max_even = (-float('inf'), 0) if nums[0] % 2 == 0 else (0, -float('inf'))`. But you can also use first number as a starting number and start iterating from the first value of the array (instead of zeroth)

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $O(n)$
- Space complexity: $O(1)$

# Code
```Rust []
impl Solution {
  pub fn max_score(nums: Vec<i32>, x: i32) -> i64 {
    let x = x as i64;
    let (mut max_odd, mut max_even) = (i32::MIN as i64, i32::MIN as i64);
    if nums[0] & 1 == 0 {
      max_even = nums[0] as i64;
    } else {
      max_odd = nums[0] as i64;
    }

    for i in 1 .. nums.len() {
      if nums[i] & 1 == 0 {
        max_even = max_even.max(max_odd - x) + nums[i] as i64;
      } else {
        max_odd = max_odd.max(max_even - x) + nums[i] as i64;       
      }
    }

    return max_even.max(max_odd);
  }
}
```
