# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Take and not take concept of dynamic programming similar to find maximum sum of not adjacent element of the array

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
For each element we have two choice either skip the element or pick the element if we pick the current and previous element is differ then we subtract x from pick and solve recursively calculate maximum sum
But slight variation in memoization 
We cant take dp[n][n] because it gives memory limit exceeded
So we take dp[n][2] here to store previously calculated answer
if our element is odd we store ans in dp[idx][1];
else in dp[idx][0];

# Complexity
- Time complexity:   O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n*2)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {

        private long fun(int idx,int nums[],int isOdd,int x,int n,long dp[][])
        {
            if(idx>=n) return 0;
            long max=0;
            if(dp[idx][isOdd]!=-1) return dp[idx][isOdd];
            long skip= fun(idx+1,nums,isOdd,x,n,dp);
            int isOddNew=(nums[idx]%2==1)?1:0;
            long pick=nums[idx]+fun(idx+1,nums,isOddNew,x,n,dp);
            if(isOdd!=isOddNew) pick-=x;
            return  dp[idx][isOdd]=Math.max(pick,skip);
        }


    public long maxScore(int[] nums, int x) {
        int isOdd=nums[0]%2==1?1:0;
        int n=nums.length;
        long dp[][]=new long[n][2];
        for(long row[]:dp)  Arrays.fill(row,-1);
        return nums[0]+fun(1,nums,isOdd,x,nums.length,dp);
    }
}
```

