# Intuition
The problem can be approached using dynamic programming with memoization. We need to find the maximum total score by visiting array positions with certain rules. At each position, we can decide to either move to the next position with the same parity or switch the parity and move to the next position. To maximize the score, we should keep track of the maximum score at each position and the parity of the previous position.

# Approach
The given code implements the dynamic programming approach using recursion with memoization. The helper function recursively calculates the maximum score starting from each position, considering the rules about moving to the next position and switching parities. The memoization is done using the dp array to store already computed results to avoid redundant calculations.

The maxScore function initializes the memoization array and then calls the helper function with the initial position set to 0 and the parity set according to the first element of the nums array.

# Complexity
Time complexity: The function calculates the maximum score for each position only once, and each calculation depends on the results of the subsequent positions. Therefore, the time complexity is O(n), where n is the number of elements in the nums array.

# Space complexity:
 The memoization array dp has a size of O(n) to store the results for each position and parity. Therefore, the space complexity is O(n). Additionally, the recursive call stack might require additional space, but it would be at most O(n) in this case.
# Code
```
class Solution {
    long long dp[100000][2];
    long long helper(vector<int>& nums, int x, int i, bool prev){
        if(i == nums.size())return 0;
        if(dp[i][prev] != -1)return dp[i][prev];
        if((nums[i] & 1) == prev){
            return dp[i][prev] = nums[i] + helper(nums, x, i + 1, prev);
        }
        return dp[i][prev] = max(1LL * nums[i] + helper(nums, x, i + 1, !prev) - x, helper(nums, x, i + 1, prev));
    }
public:
    long long maxScore(vector<int>& nums, int x) {
        memset(dp, -1, sizeof(dp));
        return nums[0] + helper(nums, x, 1, nums[0] & 1);
    }
};
```

