# Intuition & Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We have to start from the first index (thats mentioned). But need not to ge till last. We just need to maximize the score.

so, for the first index, I will always choose that element. Now the next element i will choose -
- If that element have the same parity, then perfectly I can incluse that in my score.
- If the parity of the element don't matches, then I can either change the parity by paying the charges (x) and search for the next maximum score the new parity. Or I can just skip this element and search for the next maximum score wfrom next elements with the same parity.


So this intuition seems like a 0/1 knapsack where we can have the option to choose the element or just skip the element. But this can not be always. It can be only when the parity doesn't matches.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(2n)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(2n)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    int[] nums;
    int x;
    Long[][] dp;
    private long solve(int i, int par) {

        //The base case when no more element left for calculation
        if(i == nums.length) {
            return 0;
        }

        //using memoization state to get precomputed results
        if(dp[i][par] != null) {
            return dp[i][par];
        }

        //calculating the current parity
        int currPar = nums[i]%2;
        long score = 0;

        //Checking if my current parity matches with the last 
        //choosen element parity then I can include that element 
        //in the score other case I need to seach for maximum 
        //score using 2 different options -
        // 1 - Paying the charges (x)
        // 2 - Skipping the element
        if(currPar == par) {
            score = nums[i]+solve(i+1, par);
        } else {
            score = Math.max(solve(i+1, par), ((nums[i]-x)+(solve(i+1, currPar))));
        }

        //Storing the memoization state
        return dp[i][par] = score;
    }

    public long maxScore(int[] nums, int x) {
        this.nums = nums;
        this.x = x;
        this.dp = new Long[nums.length][2];
        return nums[0]+solve(1, nums[0]%2);
    }
}
```

