# Recursion
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
we can do this using recursion by considering the subproblem as finding the maximum score if the element is picked and if the element is not picked. 
`If the element is picked, the score will be based on it's previous element.`

- Time complexity: $$O(2^n)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$ [stack space]
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int f(vector<int>& n, int x,int prev,int i){
        if(i>=n.size()) return 0;
        int pick = (n[i]%2==n[prev]%2) ? n[i]+f(n,x,i,i+1) : n[i]-x+f(n,x,i,i+1);
        int not_pick=f(n,x,prev,i+1);
        return max(pick,not_pick);
    }
    long long maxScore(vector<int>& n, int x) {
        int prev=0;
        return n[0]+f(n,x,prev,1);
    }
};
```
